snippet.textDisplay: When assuming more than ideal conditions (sun a zenith, clear sky, all efficiencys 100%), their device would need 20 square centimeters of perpendicular to the sun charging surface according to my calculations (pls correct if wrong) in order to make their claims work. As you can clearly see, they probably don't have that. But let's be real, you reading this, probably do not live near the equator. For Germany during the summer e.g. you can double that. (Still assuming clear sky, at midday). Silicon based solar cells have a efficiency of around 20%. The cool bendy super thin organic solar cells I do research on (are terrible and should not be used due to them degrading super fast, and every product with them is a scam) on commercial usecases can be assumed around 5%. So at best add another x5 . By the way, both technologies get way worse in efficiency when they get hot, therefore, a terrific idea to paint that thing black. Now, before adding these effects up, i'd like to mention, that these guys specify their testing conditions with 50 000 lux. Lux is a unit that essentialy describes how bright a human feels a light to be. This allows all sorts of shade stuff to be done to the spectrum of the test light source in order to  drive the efficiency of the solar cells up. Btw, the sun apperently has 32 000 - 100 000 lux, which should illustrate enough that this is a terrible unit to work with. The appropriate unit here would be Power aka. relate it to the solar constant. Or even better use a solar simulator. This already crys scam, but if you add up the efficiencys from before and arrive at a needed perpendicular to the sun surface of around 200 square centimeters at best. Due to the shape it can be savely assumed, that you would have to double that anyway. Factoring in weather conditions and, that it is not always midday, you will probably end up (educated guess) in the tenth of square meter region. So assuming, that my calculations are ok, you guys are pitching a scam.

snippet.textDisplay: Some gas companies around me utilize encrypted EMV, however it's not exclusive to per brand, and I don't think it was a requirement, more-so to regulate the prices more effectively. See, the ones that upgraded to it have to verify the card with an zip code, which it then utilizes to charge you the suggested gas in that region. Say if it's US $3.10 for 93 in my region, but it's US $2.88 at my work for premium, I'd then be charged for $3.10 specifically because the sister company 'in that zip code' has higher priced gas, thus allowing for more profit. Ultimately, I wish this practice was illegal, but it's not.
